Workshop Overview

This three-day hands-on workshop aims to introduce ecologists to statistical modeling using Bayesian approaches and BUGS programming. The workshop will cover

  • a brief introduction to R software and to BUGS programming conventions using the language JAGS;

  • basic statistical models and their representation in a Bayesian framework, including general linear models, generalized linear models, generalized linear mixed models;

  • specialized models in population ecology and wildlife conservation, such as occupancy modelling, population modeling, and integrated population modeling.

Prerequisites: Basic knowledge of statistics (i.e.familiarity with simple regression) and some prior exposure to R software. No prior experience with Bayesian statistical modeling is required.

1 Introduction

  • Frequentist vs Bayesian approaches (Ellison (1996), Kry (2010))
Concept/term Frequentist Bayesian
Probability Long-run relative frequency of the event in repeated experiments Degree of belief or uncertainty about an event or parameter
Parameter Fixed but unknown constant Random with probability distributions
Priors Do not specify priors Incorporate explicit prior distributions
Inference Based on sampling distributions;Relies on asymptotic theory Based on full posterior distributions; exact probabilistic inference
Error propagation Not straightforward Straightforward; handled via the posterior
  • Bayesian inference updates beliefs about parameters using Bayes theorem:

  • Prior: Initial belief before seeing data
  • Likelihood: How data relate to parameters
  • Posterior: Updated belief after data

1.1 Uninformative vs informative priors

  • Uninformative: Minimal prior knowledge
  • Informative: Incorporates existing knowledge to refine inference

1.2 Importance of probability distributions

  • They capture uncertainty at all stagespriors, likelihood, and posterior.

  • Commonly used probability distributions

Source: Royle et al.(2014)

1.3 Why MCMC?

  • Analytical calculation of posteriors is often impossible. MCMC approximates posteriors by sampling from them via Markov chains.

  • Components of MCMC

    • Burn-in: Initial samples discarded
    • Iterations: Number of samples collected
    • Initial values: Starting points
    • Convergence: Assessed by trace plots, autocorrelation, Gelman-Rubin statistic

Software

  • JAGS and BUGS languages are used for Bayesian modeling with MCMC methods.

Data

  • Simulated datasets and code for this workshop are adapted from Kry (2010) and Kry and Schaub (2012).

  • Coopers hawk dataset is provided with permission from Brian Millsap (NMSU).

Example: Proportion estimation with JAGS

Suppose we detected a particular species 4 times out of 10 visits at a given site. Estimate the probability that the species is detected on any given visit.

  • Bayesian model components:

    • Likelihood: \[ y \sim \text{Binomial}(n, \theta) \] where: \(y=4\), \(n=10\), and \(\theta\) is the unknown detection probability

    • Prior: \[ \theta \sim \text{Beta}(a, b) \\ \] A common non-informative prior is: \[ \theta \sim \text{Beta}(1, 1) \\ \]

# Specify the prior and likelihood
M0 <- "
model{
  # Likelihood
  y ~ dbin(theta, n) 
  
  # Priors
  theta ~ dbeta(1, 1)
}#End model
"

# Bundle data
data <- list(y = 4, n = 10)

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(theta = runif(1, 0, 1))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("theta")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_M0 <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
        model.file = textConnection(M0), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
        n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_M0, digits = 3)

  theme_classic()

2 General Linear Models

  • General linear models provide a broad framework for modeling relationships between a continuous response (dependent) variable (\(Y\)) and one or more predictors (\(X\)).

  • Classical hypothesis tests like t-tests, ANOVA, and ANCOVA fit naturally as special cases of general linear models.

2.1 Simple Linear Regression

  • Models relationship between \(Y\) and one continuous predictor \(X\):

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_i, \tau) \]

with

\[ \mu_i = \alpha_0 + \beta*x_i \]

where: - \(\alpha_0\) is the intercept - \(\beta\) is the slope - \(\tau = 1/\sigma^2\) (precision)

  • Bayesian model components:

    • Priors:

\[ \alpha_0, \beta \sim \text{Normal}(0, 0.0001), \quad \sigma \sim \text{Uniform}(0, 100) \]

Example

Investigate the relationship between body mass and length of the asp viper. The dataset is provided in aspviper.csv.

# Read data
av <- read.csv("aspviper.csv", header = T)
head(av, 5)
##        mass   length      pop
## 1 127.95606 63.31550 Pyrenees
## 2  90.84274 56.89404 Pyrenees
## 3 101.30909 57.85540 Pyrenees
## 4  81.63790 57.46081 Pyrenees
## 5 161.33287 64.50711 Pyrenees
# Scatter plot
ggplot(av, aes(x = length, y = mass)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Length") +
  ylab("Mass")

# JAGS code
mod_linear <- "model {
# Priors
 alpha0 ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001)
 beta ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001)
 sigma ~ dunif(0, 100) 
 tau <- pow(sigma, -2)

# Likelihood
 for (i in 1:n) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau) 
    mu[i] <- alpha0 + beta*x[i]
 }
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- av$mass
x <- as.numeric(scale(av$length)) # Standardized

data <- list(y = y, x = x, n = nrow(av))

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(alpha0 = rnorm(1, 0, 1), beta = rnorm(1, 0, 1),
                         sigma = runif(1, 0, 10))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("alpha0", "beta", "sigma")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_linear <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
        model.file = textConnection(mod_linear), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
        n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_linear, digits = 3)

2.2 Two-Sample t-Test

Suppose we want to compare the means of two groups labeled as 1 and 2.

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_i, \tau) \]

\[ \mu_i = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} \]

  • \(\alpha_1\) is the mean of group 1

  • \(\alpha_2\) is the mean of group 2

  • The classical two-sample t-test hypothesis corresponds to

\[ H_0: \alpha_2 - \alpha_1 = 0 \]

Example

Test whether the mean body mass the asp viper differs between two populations using the dataset aspviper.csv.

# Data
av1 <- av %>%
  filter(pop == "Jura" | pop == "Massif Central")

ggplot(av1, aes(x = pop, y = mass)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("Population") + 
  ylab("Mass")

# JAGS code - Means parameterization
mod_ttest <- "model {
# Priors
 for(k in 1:2) {
  alpha[k] ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001)  # group-level means
 }
 sigma ~ dunif(0, 100)
 tau <- pow(sigma, -2)

# Likelihood
 for (i in 1:n) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau) 
    mu[i] <- alpha[g[i]]
 }
# Derived parameter
 delta <- alpha[2] - alpha[1] # difference between groups
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- av1$mass
g <- as.numeric(factor(av1$pop))

data <- list(y = y, g = g, n = nrow(av1))

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(alpha = rnorm(2, 0, 1),
                         sigma = runif(1, 0, 10))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("alpha", "delta", "sigma")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_ttest <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
        model.file = textConnection(mod_ttest), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
        n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_ttest, digits = 3)

2.3 One-Way ANOVA

Suppose we have 3 groups and want to compare their means.

For 3 groups labeled 1, 2, and 3:

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_i, \tau) \]

\[ \mu_i = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} \]

Example

Evaluate whether the mean body mass of the asp viper differs among three populations using the data aspviper.csv.

ggplot(av, aes(x = pop, y = mass)) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  xlab("Population") + 
  ylab("Mass")

# JAGS code
mod_anova <- "model {
# Priors
 for(k in 1:3) {
  alpha[k] ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001)  # group-level means
 }
 sigma ~ dunif(0, 100)
 tau <- pow(sigma, -2)

# Likelihood
 for (i in 1:n) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau) 
    mu[i] <- alpha[g[i]]
 }

# Derived parameter
 delta.12 <- alpha[2] - alpha[1] # the mean difference between group 2 and group 1
 delta.13 <- alpha[3] - alpha[1]
 delta.23 <- alpha[3] - alpha[2]
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- av$mass
g <- as.numeric(factor(av$pop))

data <- list(y = y, g = g, n = nrow(av))

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(alpha = rnorm(3, 0, 1),sigma = runif(1, 0, 10))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("alpha", "delta.12", "delta.13", "delta.23", "sigma")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_anova <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
        model.file = textConnection(mod_anova), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
        n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_anova, digits = 3)

2.4 ANCOVA

ANCOVA extends ANOVA and incorporates continuous covariates to adjust group comparisons:

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_i, \tau) \]

\[ \mu_i = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} + \beta*x_i \]

  • \(\beta\) measures effect of covariate \(x_i\)
  • This model adjusts group means by \(x_i\)

Example

Assess whether the body mass differs among three asp viper populations while controlling for a continuous covariate length. Data are aspviper.csv.

ggplot(av, aes(x = length, y = mass, colour = pop)) +
  geom_point() +
  xlab("Length") + 
  ylab("Mass")

# JAGS code - Additive ANCOVA model
mod_ancova <- "model {
# Priors
 for(k in 1:3) {
  alpha[k] ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001)  
 }
 
 beta ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001) 
 
 sigma ~ dunif(0, 100)
 tau <- pow(sigma, -2)

# Likelihood
 for (i in 1:n) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau) 
    mu[i] <- alpha[g[i]] + beta*x[i]
 }
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- av$mass
g <- as.numeric(factor(av$pop))
x <- as.numeric(scale(av$length)) # Standardized

data <- list(y = y, g = g, x = x, n = nrow(av))

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(alpha = rnorm(3, 0, 1), beta = rnorm(1, 0, 1),
                         sigma = runif(1, 0, 10))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("alpha", "beta", "sigma")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_ancova <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
        model.file = textConnection(mod_ancova), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
        n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_ancova, digits = 3)

3 Generalized Linear Models (GLMs)

Generalized Linear Models (GLMs) extend general linear models to response variables that may follow different distributions than normal.

Components of a GLM

A GLM consists of three parts:

  1. Random component: The response variable \(y_i\) follows a distribution from the exponential family (e.g., Bernoulli for binary, Poisson for count data).

  2. Systematic component: A linear predictor with a single covariate

\[ \eta_i = \alpha_0 + \beta*x_{i} \]

  1. Link function: Connects the expected response \(\mu_i = E(y_i)\) to the linear predictor:

\[ g(\mu_i) = \eta_i \quad \Longleftrightarrow \quad \mu_i = g^{-1}(\eta_i) \]

3.1 Logistic Regression

Suppose we have a binary response variable \(y_i\):

\[ y_i \sim \text{Bernoulli}(p_i), \quad i=1, \ldots, n \]

where \(p_i = P(y_i=1)\).

We model \(p_i\) using the logit link function:

\[ logit(p_i) = \log\left(\frac{p_i}{1 - p_i}\right) = \eta_i \]

A model with a single numeric predictor \(x_i\) is:

\[ \eta_i = \alpha_0 + \beta*x_i \]

which implies

\[ p_i = \frac{\exp(\alpha_0 + \beta*x_i)}{1 + \exp(\alpha_0 + \beta*x_i)} \]

  • \(\alpha_0\) is the log-odds of success when \(x_i=0\)
  • \(\beta\) is the change in log-odds per unit increase in \(x_i\)

Example

Examine how terrain slope influences the detection probability of coyote. The dataset is provided in coyote.csv.

# Read data
coyote <- read.csv("coyote.csv", header = T)

#JAGS code
mod_logistic <- "model {
# Priors
 alpha0 ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001) 
 beta ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001)  
 
# Likelihood
 for (i in 1:n) {
    y[i] ~ dbern(p[i]) 
    logit(p[i]) <- alpha0 + beta*x[i] 
 }
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- coyote$detection
x <- as.numeric(scale(coyote$slope)) # standardized

data <- list(y = y, x = x, n = length(y))

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(alpha0 = rnorm(1, 0, 1), beta = rnorm(1, 0, 1))}

# Parameters monitored

#MCMC settings

3.2 Poisson Regression

Suppose we have count data \(y_i\):

\[ y_i \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda_i), \quad i=1, \ldots, n \]

We model \(\lambda_i\) using the log link function:

\[ \log(\lambda_i) = \eta_i \] A model with a single numeric predictor \(x_i\) is:

\[ \eta_i = \alpha_0 + \beta*x_i \]

which implies

\[ \lambda_i = \exp(\alpha_0 + \beta*x_i) \]

  • \(\alpha_0\) is the log expected count when \(x_i=0\)
  • \(\beta\) is the log multiplicative change in expected count per unit increase in \(x_i\)

Example

Examine the association between ectoparasite counts and wing length in dragonflies. The dataset is provided in dragonfly.csv.

    y[i] ~ dpois(lambda[i]) 
    log(lambda[i]) <- alpha0 + beta*x[i] 
 }
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- dragonfly$count
x <- as.numeric(scale(dragonfly$length)) # standardized

data <- list(y = y, x = x, n = length(y))

4 Mixed-effects models

4.1 Linear mixed-effects models (LMMs)

Linear mixed-effects models (LMMs) extend general linear models by including random effects to account for dependencies and variations arising from grouped or hierarchical data structures.

Random intercept model

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_i, \tau) \]

\[ \mu_i = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} + \beta x_i \]

\[ \alpha_j \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_{\alpha}, \tau_{\alpha}), \quad j=1, \ldots, J \]

  • \(\alpha_{\text{group}[i]}\) is a random intercept for group \(i\), capturing group-level deviations.
  • \(\beta\) measures the effect of covariate \(x_i\).
  • \(J\) is the total number of levels of the grouping variable.
  • \(\mu_{\alpha}\) and \(\tau_{\alpha}\) are hyperparameters describing the distribution of group intercepts.

Random intercept and slope model

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_i, \tau) \]

\[ \mu_i = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} + \beta_{\text{group}[i]} x_i \]

\[ \alpha_j \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_{\alpha}, \tau_{\alpha}), \quad \beta_j \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_{\beta}, \tau_{\beta}), \quad j = 1, \ldots, J \]

  • \(\alpha_{\text{group}[i]}\) and \(\beta_{\text{group}[i]}\) are random intercept and slope for group \(i\).
  • \(\mu_{\alpha}, \mu_{\beta}, \tau_{\alpha}, \tau_{\beta}\) are hyperparameters describing the population distribution of random effects.

Example

Investigate the relationship between asp viper body mass and length across 10 populations, considering variability among populations. The dataset is provided in snake.csv

# Read data
snake <- read.csv("snake.csv", header = T)

#JAGS code
mod_lmm <- "model {
# Priors
 for(k in 1:K) {
  alpha[k] ~ dnorm(mu.alpha, tau.alpha)  # random intercepts
 }
 
 mu.alpha ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001) # mean hyperparameter for random intercepts
 sigma.alpha ~ dunif(0, 100) # sd hyperparameter for random intercepts
 tau.alpha <- pow(sigma.alpha, -2)
 
  beta ~ dnorm(0, 0.0001) 

 sigma ~ dunif(0, 100) # Residual sd
 tau <- pow(sigma, -2)

# Likelihood
 for (i in 1:n) {
    y[i] ~ dnorm(mu[i], tau) 
    mu[i] <- alpha[g[i]] + beta*x[i]
 }
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- snake$mass
g <- snake$pop
x <- as.numeric(scale(snake$length)) # standardized
K <- length(unique(snake$pop))

data <- list(y = y, g = g, x = x, n = length(y), K = K)

# Initial values

                         sigma.alpha = runif(1, 0, 10), sigma = runif(1, 0, 10))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("mu.alpha", "sigma.alpha", "beta", "sigma", "alpha")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI

                     model.file = textConnection(mod_lmm), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
                     n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

4.3 Generalized linear mixed-effects models (GLMMs)

Generalized linear mixed-effects models (GLMMs) extend GLMs by including random effects to account for individual- or group-level variability through hierarchical structures.

Binary response variable

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Bernoulli}(p_i) \]

\[ \text{logit}(p_i) = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} + \beta x_i \]

with

\[ \alpha_j \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_{\alpha}, \tau_{\alpha}), \quad j=1, ..., J \]

  • Here, \(p_i\) is the probability of success.
  • \(\alpha_{\text{group}[i]}\) models the group-specific random intercept.
  • \(\beta\) is the fixed effect of covariate \(x_i\).

Poisson response variable

\[ y_i \sim \mathrm{Poisson}(\lambda_i) \]

\[ \log(\lambda_i) = \alpha_{\text{group}[i]} + \beta x_i \]

with

\[ \alpha_j \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_{\alpha}, \tau_{\alpha}), \quad j=1, ..., J \]

  • \(\lambda_i\) is the expected count for observation \(i\).
  • \(\alpha_{\text{group}[i]}\) is the group-specific random intercept.
  • \(\beta\) is the fixed effect coefficient for covariate \(x_i\).

Random intercept and slope

The above models can be extended to include random slopes.

5 Occupancy Models

Occupancy models are hierarchical logistic regression models that estimate species occurrence while accounting for imperfect detection.

5.1 Single-Season Occupancy Models

  • Basic sampling design

Key assumption: The site is closed during the survey periods and there are no false positives.

Model description

Ecological (state) process

\[ z_i \sim Bernoulli(\psi_i), \quad logit(\psi_i) = \beta_0 + \beta*x_i \]

Observation process

\[ y_{ij}|z_i \sim Bernoulli(z_i*p_{ij}), \quad logit(p_{ij}) = \alpha_0 + \alpha*x_{ij} \] - Here, \(\psi_i\) is the probability of species presence (occupancy probability), and \(p_{ij}\) is the probability of detecting the species given presence.

Example

Analyze data from three repeated surveys at 100 sites to determine how humidity affects the occurrence of Chiltern gentian. The dataset is provided in gentian.csv.

# Read data
gentian <- read.csv("gentian.csv", header = T)

#JAGS code
mod_occ <- "model {
# Priors
 beta0 ~ dunif(-10, 10) #dnorm(0, 1e-6)

 beta ~ dunif(-10, 10) #dnorm(0, 1e-6)  
 
 alpha0 ~ dunif(-10, 10) #dnorm(0, 1e-6)
 
# Likelihood
   for (i in 1:R){
        #Ecological process
        z[i] ~ dbern(psi[i])
        logit(psi[i]) <- beta0 + beta*x[i]
        for (j in 1:T){
            #Observation process
            y[i,j] ~ dbern(pe[i,j])
            pe[i,j] <- z[i]*p[i,j]  # Can only be detected if z=1
            logit(p[i,j]) <- alpha0
        } 
    }
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- gentian[,1:3]
x <- as.numeric(scale(gentian$humidity)) # standardized
R <- nrow(y)
T <- ncol(y)

data <- list(y = y, x = x, R = R, T = T)

# Initial values
zst <- apply(y, 1, max) # initial values for true/latent states
inits <- function(){list(beta0 = rnorm(1, 0, 1), beta = rnorm(1, 0, 1), 
                         alpha0 = rnorm(1, 0, 1), 
                         z = zst)}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("beta0", "beta", "alpha0")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_occ <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
                     model.file = textConnection(mod_occ), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
                     n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_occ, digits = 3)

6 State-Space Models for Population Counts

State-space models are hierarchical models composed of two sets of equations: 1) the state process, and 2) the observation process.

For population count data: - The state process equation describes the true but unknown (latent) population size over time. For a population that grows exponentially, it can be expressed as

\[ N_{t+1} = N_t \lambda_t \] \[ \lambda_t \sim \mathrm{Normal}(\mu_\lambda, \tau_\lambda) \] where \(\mu_\lambda\) is the long-term growth rate of the population.

  • The observation process equation links the observed count data (\(y\)) with the true population size (\(N\)).

\[ y_t \sim \mathrm{Normal}(N_t, \tau_y) \]

Example

Analyze the growth rate of an ibex population monitored over 25 years. The dataset is provided in ibex.csv.

# Read data
ibex <- read.csv("ibex.csv", header = T)

#JAGS code
mod_ss <- "model {
# Priors
N.est[1] ~ dunif(2, 10)
mu.lambda ~ dunif(0, 10) 
sigma.lambda ~ dunif(0,10) # process sd (environmental stochasticity)
tau.lambda <- pow(sigma.lambda, -2)

sigma.obs ~ dunif(0,10) # observation error sd
tau.obs <- pow(sigma.obs, -2)

# Likelihood
   #State process
   for (t in 1:(T-1)){
        lambda[t] ~ dnorm(mu.lambda, tau.lambda)
        N.est[t+1] <- N.est[t]*lambda[t]
   }
   #Observation process
   for (t in 1:T){
        y[t] ~ dnorm(N.est[t], tau.obs)
    } 
}
"

# Bundle data
y <- ibex$count/10  # rescale the data by a factor of 0.1
T <- length(y)

data <- list(y = y, T = T)

# Initial values
inits <- function(){list(mu.lambda = runif(1, 0.1, 2), sigma.lambda = runif(1, 0, 5),
                         sigma.obs = runif(1, 0, 5),
                         N.est = c(runif(1,2,10), rep(NA,(T-1))))}

# Parameters monitored
params <- c("mu.lambda", "sigma.lambda", "sigma.obs", "N.est")

#MCMC settings
ni <- 5000
nb <- 2000
nt <- 5
nc <- 3

# Running the model using JagsUI
out_ss <- jagsUI(data = data, inits = inits, parameters.to.save = params, 
                     model.file = textConnection(mod_ss), n.chains = nc, n.thin = nt, 
                     n.iter = ni, n.burnin = nb, verbose = FALSE)

# Print output
print(out_ss, digits = 3)

7 Matrix population models

  • Common tools for studying the demography of wildlife populations

  • The matrix population model is written as

\[ {\bf N}_{t+1} = {\bf AN}_{t} \]

where, \({\bf N}_{t}\): a vector containing the number of individuals in each age or stage class at time \(t\)

\({\bf A}\): a projection matrix composed of vital rates (e.g.survival and fecundity rates)

Example: Construction of a lifecycle graph and projection matrix

Consider a population with 2 age classes (juvenile and adults (\(\geq\) 1 year old)), with the following assumptions:

  • The population is censused after breeding

  • Age at first breeding is 1 year

  • Survival varies by age (\(S_0\), \(S_1\))

  • Fecundity does not vary by age (\(F\))

The life cycle of this population is given by

The corresponding female-based matrix population model is

\[ {\bf N}_{t+1} = {\bf AN}_{t} \] \[ \begin{bmatrix} N_J \\ N_A \end{bmatrix}_{t+1} = \begin{bmatrix} S_0\frac{F}{2} & S_1\frac{F}{2} \\ S_0 & S_1 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} N_J \\ N_A \end{bmatrix}_t \] Given the projection matrix A, one can compute its eigenvalues and eigenvectors.

  • popbio: An R package for eigenvalues and eigenvectors analysis ({Stubben & Milligan (2007))}

  • Biological interpretation of eigenvalues and eigenvectors of A:

    • Dominant eigenvalue: Asymptotic growth rate (\(\lambda\))

    • Right eigenvector (standardized): Stable age/stage distribution

    • Left eigenvector (scaled): ** Reproductive value**

Example

Barclay et al.(2011) developed a two-stage, post-breeding, female-based matrix population model for burrowing owls, assuming juvenile females reproduce at the end of their first year at the same rate as adults. The estimated annual juvenile survival (\(Sj\)), adult survival (\(Sa\)), and fecundity (\(F\)) were 0.24, 0.47, and 1.80, respectively. Calculate the long-term population growth rate, stable age distribution and reproductive values for burrowing owl population. Perform sensitivity and elasticity analyses to identiJ which vital rates most influence lambda.

# Mean demographic estimates. 
sj <- 0.24 
sa <- 0.47
F <- 3.6

stage <- c("J", "A")

#Projection matrix - note that fecundity is reduced by 1/2 to convert to 
#   females produced per female, assuming 50:50 sex ratio at fledging.
A <- matrix(c(sj*F*0.5, sa*F*0.5,
              sj, sa),nrow=2,ncol=2,byrow=T,dimnames=list(stage,stage))
print(A)
##       J     A
## J 0.432 0.846
## A 0.240 0.470
# Asymptotic growth rate - dominant eigenvalue.
lambda(A)
## [1] 0.902
# Stable age/stage distribution - right eigenvector.
stable.stage(A)
##         J         A 
## 0.6428571 0.3571429
# Reproductive value - left eigenvector. 
reproductive.value(A)
##        J        A 
## 1.000000 1.958333
# Sensitivity and elasticity analysis of vital rates. Note, need to rename 
#   parameters to avoid overwriting.
tvr <- list(S1 = sj, S2 = sa, 
            F = F)
           
tel <- expression(S1*F*0.5, S2*F*0.5,
                  S1, S2)
    
options(scipen=999) # turn it off the sci notation

x <- vitalsens(tel, tvr) # function to calculate sensitivity and elasticity
print(x)
##    estimate sensitivity elasticity
## S1     0.24        1.80  0.4789357
## S2     0.47        1.00  0.5210643
## F      3.60        0.12  0.4789357
